Comment_contributor: In counting a series it is e ta, but after that rua, ’olu, &c., without the Verbal Particle e
A single thing is not eta but tata
This [Verbal Particle e] is never used with walu and siwe
This [Verbal Particle e] is never used with walu and siwe
[<tanahulu>, with <n> in italics]; [The Verbal Particle e] is sometimes [used] with taŋahulu [<tanahulu>, with <n> in italics]
[<tanarau>, with <n> in italics]; the word for hundred means the double frond, counted on both sides, as the word for ten means the double handful of fingers.
There is a word in use in Florida and Bugotu, mola, which is used indefinitely for a great number beyond count; and this, but doubtfully, is given in Malanta and Ulawa for a thousand.
[<mola>, with <m> in italics, = “nasal”]; The exact number of a thousand is conveyed by mola when yams are counted.
A thousand cocoa-nuts is qela ni niu
